segments.text: interviewing Dr. Glenn Johnson in the Center for Teaching Excellence.
Dr. Johnson has been at Texas A&M since 1967, which is a couple of years before the College of Education actually became a college.

And Dr. Johnson, I would like for you if you would just kind of think back to the time that you arrived and the things that have happened and the changes that have taken place within the College of Education
your arrival, just some of the highlights.
Obviously, that's a big order, very open-ended.
Well, let's see.
I came a little early.
They had some funds to bring me in in mid-August, so I was actually on the job a few months before the beginning of the year.
You came in in what capacity?
Funds for what?
Travel, consulting, and so forth.
It was the way in those days to get new faculty, move,
and on the job before they actually had courses to teach, et cetera.
So you did not have a course at the time?
No.
What department were you with originally?
At that time, in August, it was called the Department of Education and Psychology.
And at the end of that month, that no longer existed.
It became the Department of Education.
And the Department of Psychology opened its doors September 1 of 67.

So during that first year, I was under the impression that there was going to be some great growth take place at Texas A&M University, and particularly in education, because they had only recently begun to advertise that it was coeducational.
Was that in 68 or 67?
OK.
So when we met with our students for the first time the first week of September, we found out that at Texas A&M University, there were approximately 600 girls enrolled.
And a large proportion of them were in the Department of Education.
Our projections then were that this was probably going to double annually.
because of the now-released publicity on it.
There had been a tendency not to really banter this.
That there were girls here?
Yeah, that there were girls here.
So the word had gotten out in the informal communication net, and that's why we had 600.
But now they were starting to publicize it with flyers and bulletins and news releases, etc.,
And in retrospect, that held true for several years.
It just seemed like we were doubling our enrollment every year.
So 600 girls, 1,200 girls, 2,400.
How long did that keep up?
For years, because I think it must have been around, you could check someone in the university, I'll bet around 70,
778, we were probably at 10,000 girls.
That's a guess.
I'll take that.
Interesting.
Yeah, I think even that first year I was there in 1967, 68, the informal communication that was saying that we were going to become a college of education, that the growth
was so rampant in the demand, so great, that this would take place.
And of course, later we would find out that President Rutter, who had hired Frank Hubert to be the dean of the College of Arts and Sciences, gave Dean Hubert a choice.
Basically said, Frank, would you like to be
Dean of Arts and Sciences as you are now, or would you like to be the Dean of the new College of Education when it opens?
Did that comment surprise anybody, that he chose to go to the Dean of the College of Education?
It didn't surprise me, because I'd heard him talk about this.
He just felt like with all of his experience in the public schools and being in charge of certification for the state of Texas at one time with the Texas Education Agency,
that his next thrust, his next contribution to Texas A&M University would be in the new College of Education.
And he had a dream that it would always be called the new College of Education.
I can recall him addressing the new department heads when they formed the new departments and saying that he hoped that always
would be the new college of education.
We didn't want things to become entrenched where people started building their empires and would have nothing to do with the other departments.
Were there any specific political or sociological things that might have impacted the tremendous growth other than, of course, the admittance of girls?
And that was definitely one of the largest.
That was the biggest, I think.
I think as soon as they opened it up to the girls, it just brought a totally different cultural look, atmosphere.
Everything was very, very positive.
Because it grew so fast, as a professor,
Did you feel that this had a definite change on the way you were able to interact with students or work with students?
I didn't feel that way because they'd always taken such great pride in being able to interact with the students and holding the student as an extremely important part of the university.
At least in our department and in the college in general, I felt like they tried to maintain that, but they would
go the extra mile to maintain that atmosphere.
The mission of a land grant institution is the triad of teaching, research, and service.
In your opinion, from your point of view, perspective, has that changed in the two eras with emphasis on one more so than another?
Only slightly.
For example, in 1967,
Dr. Jerry Salek, who was also a graduate of Columbia University, although I didn't know him at all until we both arrived in August.
Dr. Salek and I, along with some personnel who were already here, Lorene Robey, Dr. Lane Murray, Dr. Bill Graves, and Dr. Roger Harrell, under leadership of Dr. Paul Hensley, opened
The education program in 1967 was a totally different way of looking at teacher preparation.
We implemented what was called a block program.
We had the students all day, every day, five days a week for the first six weeks.
And we had all our methods, courses, and educational psychology all being team or cooperatively team taught.
first six weeks, and then the students went out and student taught all day, every day, five days a week for the rest of the semester.
During that same semester, Jerry and I brought in interaction analysis training and micro-teaching training, which was very, very new.
In fact, no one, to our knowledge, was doing any of that in the entire state of Texas.
All they were doing was talking about it.
Stanford had a program.
The Far West Lab had done something.
So it was pretty innovative at that time.
It's not now.
It's old hat.
But in 1967, it was very innovative to bring all of that together.
Interaction analysis, micro teaching, block program.
And I think that started to build a reputation across the state.

I heard Dean Hubert for probably the next three years say over and over, when I go traveling throughout the state, people keep referencing the work that we're doing in the block program interaction analysis and micro-teachings.
The word was spreading.
Also, I think another thing that had an impact was the region service centers had been established.
When were those established?
Do you know?
I want to say 66, 67.
But the key point there was that the Region Service Center in Houston invited Texas A&M to take $100,000 and develop the first training model for...
early childhood education preparation.
So we did.
We spent that year developing a model and field testing it.
In the summer, we had people like Mary Bassett.
And we brought in some experts from across the country to talk to that first group that were the field test.
And that became really the first model.
We sent that to the Texas Education Agency.
It seemed to have a good impact, so it surprised everyone that Texas A&M, which was so new to this field, would be the ones to come up with the first endorsement of a kindergarten certificate.
So do you think, does that mean then that actually A&M was in the forefront from the beginning as a college of education, not so much that it
you know, evolved from infancy to, I mean, in other words, it came on pretty strong from the very beginning.
Yes, and I think that reputation, it took a long time, you know, for people to recognize that.
I think now, you know, if you talk to people across the state, I think they like what Texas A&M has done as teacher.
How about nationwide?
Does it stand still?
No, we still, no, we suffer that same image
that we suffered back in 67.
People just don't know outside the state.
They just don't know what Texas A&M is.
Normally if you run into people who have never been here or are not part of the Southwest Conference, their first question is, where is that?
So you're not talking about the College of Education as such, but just A&M in general?
A&M in general, and therefore we're caught up in, of course, the College of Education.
What about the emphasis on research?
I mean, of course, this was more major service.
It's been a subtle shift.
In those days, I think you would have called it more scholarly productivity.
What we were doing research-wise would have been scholarly productivity.

It's only in recent years, probably the last three years, that there's been this very subtle shift to, although scholarly research is still done, there's a shift to recognizing dollars, how much money is coming in that can be earmarked as grantsmanship money, which is the standard.
type of criterion that research universities have used for years to measure their productivity.
How many dollars can you bring in from outside funds as far as your research goes?
Now, I have picked up from other interviews that Dean Hubert's emphasis was that you don't fill a college with soft monies.
Is that what you're referring to, the grants that you need to have it?
Hard money.
You need to have state support.
Right.
And the university needs to provide that undergirding, that foundation, if you're going to have a solid program.
So has that changed then now?
Is there more emphasis on the soft monies, or is it still pretty?
No, I think you still have to have that basic foundation that Dean Huber talked about.
But I think with the new administration across the whole university, there's more recognition being given
to outside funding supplementing or complementing what you're doing.
Because again, see, that's how your ranking and ratings with your peers across the country come about.
And I think the recent Carnegie labeling of universities and colleges in the United States bears that out.
There are only two, level one.
research universities in the entire state of Texas, UT Austin, Texas A&M.
None of the others in the state made that level one.
In fact, they didn't make level two.
You have to drop to the third classification before you start picking up Houston, Tech, and the rest.
Tell me about the Center for Teaching Excellence and how that came about, because I know that's your... Oh, about 1971,
I started teaching the EDCI 601 college teaching course.
And I had a few teaching assistants out of chemistry in that course.
And they kept going back and telling their coordinator, who at that time was Dr. David Brooks, who's now at the University of Nebraska, about what we were doing in this course.
And they were saying everybody should have that.
So Dave Brooks talked to me, and I said, why don't we run a one-week workshop for him?
So we set up a workshop.
And I think Dave had about, let's say, 30 chemistry TAs come in for a week.
And to really recognize his interest, he sat in with them.
He attended every session of that five-day workshop.
By the time Thursday came, they were saying, this is great, we need to get Dean Kunze from the graduate college over here.
So Kunze did agree to come over that Friday morning, and they hammered away at George for about an hour about how great this was, and T.A.
should have this, and they ought to get recognition for it, and so forth.
So that was, to me, the first thing that was going to lay the groundwork for a center, because Kunze did respond to that.
He went to the academic policy people, the deans and vice presidents.
And the very next year, they offered graduate assistants teaching an extra $25 per month, stipend if they took
a special course that I then set up for the teaching assistants.
I closed it at 48.
We had 48 enroll in that, which was a big... Was that the first one?
That was the first one.
Well, then the economic... What course, excuse me one second, what course was that?
What was it called?
I want to say it was called 678.
Under what department?
It was in EDCI.
ED?
EDCI, Education and Criterion.
Yeah, right.
Okay, EDCI and...
I think it was called 678.
And it was a teaching of?
I think it was the analysis of college teaching.
OK.
I'll look that up.
But that course is defunct now.
OK. And the history of that is because during that first year is when the economy fell out in the state.
And they didn't have that kind of money.
And when you don't have the money and the carrot, then you don't have the enrollment.
What was that year again, when you had the 48 students?
That must have been...
I can probably look that up.
I think that was in 1972.
Okay.
If you have anything, any documents or things that might contribute to the demographics or the...
I would be happy to make copies and bring them back to you.
This will be interesting for me to look up again.
At your old book?
Uh-huh.
So then there was no center at the time.
It was just a course.
No, it was just a course.
That's right, just a course.
And the center then did not actually become...
a center as such until what year?
Let's see, 1983, January 16, 1983.
And where did the funding come from?
The initial funding came from the development office, and that was the first year.
And then the second year, it came from the Permanent University Fund, Available Fund from the Permanent University Fund.
And we have been on those funds ever since.
How many people on your staff?
I have one full-time secretary, and I have one full-time training specialist, and I have one graduate assistant on teaching, and one work study.
Do you also still teach?
Yes.
NADCI?
NADCI.
What courses?
EDCI 601, college teaching.
EDCI 6... No, it doesn't matter.
It's the special topics course.
Okay, now, what is the primary function of the center right now?
Okay, I can give that to you.
Okay.
History and the functions.
Thank you.
OK. And I've been getting some of the newsletters.
Do you still publish that?
Yes.
On a, let's see, is it how?
Monthly basis.
A monthly basis.
Just September through May.
And what kind of collaborative effort do you have with other departments and other colleges?
Do you work very closely with?
What I use is a network.
I have one representative from each of the 10 academic colleges.
So I do wear two hats for the College of Education.
The dean just asked me to play both roles.
And we meet a couple of times a year just to coordinate and talk about issues and directions.
And I get ideas from them.
So anything that I do, I usually work through the representative who stays in touch with his college dean.
For example, we give out $1,000 incentive grants to faculty members who want to do something innovative in teaching.
Those flow through that representative.
So they know what their allocation is, and then if they have 10 applicants and only three $1,000 awards, they narrow those 10 down to three.
They send those over to me, and I'm the last check on the proposal, and if it's fine, good.
I just transfer the money over to their college.
And then they're in charge of the bookkeeping at the college, the dean's level, in charge of the bookkeeping.
When they're through, they send the final report to me, which we file.
Can you tell me a little bit, perhaps over these many years that you've been here, maybe either a highlight or what you feel maybe has been your
your greatest contribution, or even an observation of something that I might not find in these documents that would be stringent?
I would have to identify the Center for Teaching Excellence even more so than the four and a half years as head of that new department of curriculum instruction.
Those were growth years and very critical years.
Because when the old Department of Education closed,
It had 1,800 majors.
And when the new college opened, our department had 1,800 majors, which was beyond any projection that had been laid.
So we were short on graduate assistants.
We were short on faculty members.
We were short on resources.
And those first half years were critical building years.
So you were the first head of the EDCI.
And what year was that when we got organized?
When I stepped down, that's what they gave me.
Well, then it was the same year.
In other words, did the department open when the college opened?
It was part of the new college.
Yes.

The only departments that existed at the time were the departments of health and physical education, which was in the arts and sciences, the department of ag education, which is a liaison arrangement, the department of industrial education, which was with engineering, and the old department of education.
And they simply split the old department of education into three new departments.
Oh, OK.
EDCI, Ed Administration, and Ed Psych.
And the majors within education then chose which of these five they were going to.
Health and PE, Industrial Ed, EDCI, Ed Administration, or Ed Psych.
And you ended up with 18?
That's right.
And that was all there was in the whole department before?
College.
Does that mean that they all chose EDCI?
No.
What happened is you had
Again, a tremendous growth factor so that you'd have to check, but I'll bet Ed Psych probably opened to about 300 and Ed Aid to probably about 300.
But we opened to 1,800.
And, of course, it lost a number of faculty members to Ed Psych and Ed Administration.
So those were formative years, but I would still say the center has been my most exciting work.
Because Dean Hubert and I tried two different times from around 1972 till he stepped down to get a center established.
And there were always too many priorities.
The growth of the university was too great, and they could not come up with the funding.
It was when Dean Corrigan came in and the committees were formed that they finally could catch their breath a little bit.
And that's when they formed the center.
Do you see anything in the near future or even the more distant future that will impact the College of Education?
I know there's some really
scary things going on right now that people are very apprehensive about besides the economy, just the changes in education and the reforms.
Oh, I see.
Sure.
What do you perceive the future to be for the college, like, say, from the year 2000 and beyond, possibly?
It all depends on the economy.
Because without the money, you just can't do it.
Now, if the resources are there, we may see some very dramatic shifts.
We may see more collaboration between the university and the public school setting.
Although I think it's good now, I think there'll be even more take place.
I think you may see, in the 21st century, you may see more efforts to become more technologically oriented, more interactive television, more work with microcomputers.
But again, see, that's all tied into the economy.
If you don't have the money, you can't move that direction.
I think the last estimate I saw to completely establish two locations with interactive television ran about close to $400,000, say, for two locations.
Well, that's a lot of money.
Do you feel that the center, though, in itself is
pretty secure?
I have no idea.
Does it come up year after year for refunding or how does that work?
It's a good question.
I think all centers and all non-line item operations are always looked at annually in light of the economics of the whole situation.
For example, when
When you want to move in a certain direction and you need the monies and you don't have it from the state, then the only place you can look is the available fund.
And you have to look and see what's in the available fund.
And are there places where you need to cut back in order to get this new thrust?
So in that light, everyone would be vulnerable.
Co-op, continuing ed, study abroad,
international programs, name any of the programs that are operating out of available funds.
They can become vulnerable if a new thrust comes.
Very good.
Is there anything that we haven't covered that I had in the questions that you might have wanted to discuss?
What I'm looking at in my paper is the Hubert era and the Corrigan era and then of course a little bit of the
interim under Dr. Limbacher, I'm not going to do leadership styles as such because that would be too involved.
Just more of the perceptions of the individuals that were here because so many of them have been here since the beginning.
And a lot of it is attributed to Dean Hubert's ability to tap the... Yeah, I don't think the College of Education would have moved as quickly if it hadn't been for Frank Hubert.
I think he knew the state.
He knew the politics of the state.
He knew how to, quote, grease the tracks so that this thing could become operational in less than two years from the time it was proposed, which is a remarkable feat.
But it's kind of like Earl Rudder.
See, Earl Rudder's the only one who could have made this a co-educational university.
I think during the Hubert era, I would say the thrust was internal within the state.
The concentration was to establish ourselves with the agency, with the coordinating board, with the people of the state of Texas.
Under Corrigan, he has continued with that thrust, but we have moved into more of a national light with the Holmes study and other efforts.
And of course, Corrigan came.
from a national background and national reputation.
So it's a logical transition to move from focus internally within the state to focus more, retain that, but also start looking at your image nationally.
And I think that will pay dividends eventually.
Is it a very gradual?
Oh, my guess is a 10 to 15 year gap.
In other words, if we were doing 15 years from now exactly what we're doing today, we would have far more recognition 15 years from now.
It's that gap that's there before people say, oh, Texas A&M is a college of education, and recognize what it does.
Do you feel that there will always be a college of education?
I'm even picking up some comments like, well, maybe there won't even be one, but I've never really...
I feel...
Now, I have no evidence of this, but I feel like places like Texas A&M and UT Austin in particular need a college of education.
They're supposed to be the flagship universities.
They should be doing the best work possible in all fields.
And education is one of the fields.
So I think a college of education should do this.
And we'll survive, hopefully.
Hopefully.
Even though there are going to be probably some drastic changes, even in the teacher preparation.
Will that affect your center at all?
No.
Center is a separate entity.
It's the university center for teaching excellence.
Right.
Of course, directly to the office of provost.
It is not detached to any department or college.
Now, I have
tremendous benefits being attached to the College of Education because Dean Corrigan and Bill Peters have recognized the contribution of the Center.
So I probably have some benefits that others might not enjoy as much because they've been very supportive.
Dr. Johnson, I really appreciate your time and your effort and I think it's wonderful and I want to keep on getting these newsletters.
